    "instruction": "From metric.csv return the list of unique kpi_name values (limit 50) for each of these cmdb_ids: frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, frontend2-0, checkoutservice-0, checkoutservice-1, checkoutservice-2, productcatalogservice-0, productcatalogservice-1, productcatalogservice-2. Return a compact JSON/dict mapping cmdb_id -> {unique_kpi_names_list (up to 50), total_rows_for_that_cmdb_id} and limit output to these 10 components only."
}

{
    "analysis": "We inspected metric KPI names for the main candidate components (frontend-0/1/2, frontend2-0, checkoutservice-0/1/2, productcatalogservice-0/1/2). The KPI name sets include many container-level metrics (container.* CPU/memory/io) and some application KPIs. Error logs and trace volumes point to frontend pods as primary suspects, so next we must compute global thresholds for each component-KPI time series (using the full available series in metric.csv) before restricting to the incident window. These thresholds (e.g., P95 and P5) will let us detect anomalies within March 20 2022 20:30–21:00.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, for each of these cmdb_ids: frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, frontend2-0, checkoutservice-0, checkoutservice-1, checkoutservice-2, productcatalogservice-0, productcatalogservice-1, productcatalogservice-2, aggregate the full-time series by kpi_name and compute compact global statistics: {kpi_name, count, p95, p5, mean, max}. Return a JSON/dict mapping each cmdb_id to a list of its kpi entries. Limit to at most 50 kpi entries per component and only include the numeric fields specified. Keep output strictly bounded and compact."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous Executor attempt to compute global KPI statistics for 10 components failed. To make the request lighter and ensure success, we should restrict the scope to the highest-priority candidates (frontend pods) first because metrics, traces, and error_logs concentrate on frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2 and frontend2-0. From their global KPI statistics we can detect anomalies during the incident window and then expand if needed.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, for cmdb_ids frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, frontend2-0 only: aggregate the full available time series by kpi_name (do NOT filter by incident time yet) and compute for each component-KPI the following global statistics: count, p95, p5, mean, max. Return a JSON/dict mapping each cmdb_id to a list of its KPI entries: {kpi_name, count, p95, p5, mean, max}. Limit to at most 30 KPI entries per component (select the KPI_names with highest counts if there are more). Keep outputs strictly compact and bounded."
}

{
    "analysis": "We obtained global statistics (count, p95, p5, mean, max) for container KPIs of the four highest-priority frontend pods. Key findings from the global stats: frontend-2 has the highest CPU usage (p95 ~0.8001) and larger filesystem usage (~114 MB); frontend2-0 (on node-6) shows measurable CPU throttling (p95 throttled_seconds ~0.0688 and throttled_periods p95 ~1.775) while its raw CPU usage is lower. According to the workflow, the next step is anomaly detection within the incident window using these global thresholds (P95 as the primary threshold). We must now extract metric points in the incident time range and detect consecutive anomalies where a KPI value exceeds its global p95 (or falls below p5 for metrics where low values indicate issues). From that, we can derive earliest anomaly times and narrow candidate faults for further trace/log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv, filter rows for cmdb_id in [frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, frontend2-0] and timestamp between 1647779400 and 1647779999 inclusive (the incident window). For each row, mark it an anomaly if value >= the previously computed global p95 for that component-KPI (use p5 only if you detect a KPI that should be low-violations; for now apply p95 rule). Return a compact, bounded JSON with two parts:\n1) anomalies_list: up to top 50 anomaly rows sorted by timestamp ascending, each item {cmdb_id, kpi_name, timestamp, value, p95_threshold, breach = value - p95_threshold}.\n2) anomaly_summary: for each cmdb_id and kpi_name that has anomalies, return {cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_breach (max value-p95)}. Limit anomaly_summary entries to top 50. Keep outputs compact."
}

{
    "analysis": "We ran anomaly detection within the incident window (1647779400–1647779999) using component-KPI global P95 thresholds. The Executor returned up to 50 anomaly rows (sample shows many entries at timestamp 1647779400) and an anomaly_summary listing KPI-level anomaly counts and earliest anomaly timestamps. Earliest anomaly observed is 1647779400. Anomalies concentrate on frontend pods (frontend-0 is the component with the most anomalies). To proceed to fault identification we must convert these per-point anomalies into consecutive anomalous sub-series (fault runs) for each component-KPI to find persistent faults and their first occurrence times.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the anomalies_out table already stored in the kernel (if it does not exist, re-generate anomalies using metric.csv, the previously computed per-component per-kpi p95 thresholds, and the same incident time filter):\n- Group anomalies by cmdb_id and kpi_name and detect consecutive anomalous runs where adjacent anomaly timestamps differ by <=60 seconds (i.e., consecutive minutes).\n- For each run produce a compact record: {cmdb_id, kpi_name, start_timestamp, end_timestamp, length_minutes, anomaly_count, p95_threshold (median or first available), max_value_in_run, max_breach_in_run}.\n- Filter out runs with length_minutes < 2 (treat isolated single-minute spikes as noise).\n- Return up to top 50 runs sorted by length_minutes desc then max_breach desc as a JSON/list. If anomalies_out is empty, return an empty list and a message indicating no anomalies to group."
}

{
    "analysis": "Last step attempted to group per-point anomalies into consecutive multi-minute anomaly runs, but the kernel did not return any runs (runs_out was missing/None). From earlier outputs we do have many per-minute anomalies concentrated at the earliest timestamp 1647779400 (2022-03-20 20:30:00 UTC+8) and anomaly_summary shows many KPI-level anomalies on frontend pods (frontend-0/1/2). Because multi-minute runs were not produced, we cannot yet pick a single sustained KPI fault; however the anomaly concentration at 1647779400 is a strong signal for the root cause occurrence time. To localize the root cause component we should use traces at that timestamp to find which downstream service calls show abnormal durations or errors, since traces will indicate the last faulty service in the call chain. Therefore the next step is to inspect trace.csv at the earliest anomaly timestamp for frontend pods and their downstream services to find high-latency or high-error traces.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From trace.csv filter rows with timestamp == 1647779400 and cmdb_id in [frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, frontend2-0, checkoutservice-0, checkoutservice-1, checkoutservice-2, productcatalogservice-0, productcatalogservice-1, productcatalogservice-2]. Return the top 20 rows sorted by value descending with columns: {timestamp, cmdb_id, trace_name, value}. Also return a compact count of how many trace rows at that timestamp exist per cmdb_id (limit to these cmdb_ids). Keep output strictly bounded."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have followed preprocess and initial anomaly detection steps. Global P95 thresholds for container KPIs were computed for key frontend pods (frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, frontend2-0). Using those thresholds, metric anomalies within the incident window (1647779400–1647779999) were detected and are concentrated at the very start of the window: earliest anomaly timestamp = 1647779400 (2022-03-20 20:30:00 UTC+8). Anomaly counts and sustained anomalies (attempted grouping) pointed to frontend pods as the dominant anomalous components, but an explicit multi-minute run table was not produced. Trace snapshot at 1647779400 shows heavy activity originating from frontend pods (very high trace.self.row_count for frontend-0/1/2 and frontend2-0) and notable downstream traffic to productcatalogservice pods (many trace.from_frontend.* row_count values around ~190–201). Error logs are also concentrated on frontend pods per earlier summaries (frontend-2/0/1 with many warning messages). From these results we can already infer the failure onset time is 1647779400 and that frontend pods are involved, but we need log-level evidence (error_logs.csv and log.csv) to determine the exact root cause component and the underlying reason (e.g., resource exhaustion, throttling, process crashes, network errors). Next step: inspect error_logs and aggregated log metrics for the frontend pods within the incident window to extract earliest error messages, severity, and any log.error_count spikes.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From error_logs.csv and log.csv, restrict to timestamp between 1647779400 and 1647779999 inclusive and cmdb_id in [frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, frontend2-0]. Return two compact results as JSON/dict:\n1) error_logs_summary: for each cmdb_id return {cmdb_id, row_count, earliest_timestamp, latest_timestamp, top_messages: list of up to 10 distinct messages with their counts (message, count)} — order messages by count desc.\n2) log_metrics_summary: from log.csv group by cmdb_id and log_name and return for each group {cmdb_id, log_name, row_count, sum_value, max_value, earliest_timestamp, latest_timestamp}. Limit log_metrics_summary to top 20 rows ordered by row_count desc then sum_value desc. Keep outputs strictly bounded and compact."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed preprocessing and initial anomaly detection steps. Global P95 thresholds were computed for key frontend pods; metric anomalies within the incident window concentrate at timestamp 1647779400 (2022-03-20 20:30:00 UTC+8). Trace data at that timestamp shows very high trace.self.row_count on frontend-0/1/2 and frontend2-0 and heavy downstream call counts to productcatalogservice pods. Error logs and log metrics are heavily concentrated on frontend pods between 20:30 and ~20:40: error_logs.csv shows hundreds of warning messages from frontend-2/0/1 and log.csv shows elevated log.error_count values (frontend-2 sum 235, frontend-0 sum 231, frontend-1 sum 201 across the window). Multi-minute anomaly-run grouping was not produced earlier, but the concentration of anomalies and logs at 1647779400 makes that timestamp the likely failure onset. To determine the exact root cause component and reason, we need the concrete text of the error messages and the per-minute error_count time series (to find the first minute with errors) for the frontend pods. This will let us confirm whether the problem is application-level (failed to retrieve upstream resource), network-related, or resource exhaustion (e.g., CPU throttling seen on frontend2-0).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "1) From error_logs.csv filter rows where timestamp between 1647779400 and 1647779999 inclusive and cmdb_id in [frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, frontend2-0]. Group by cmdb_id and message; for each group return {cmdb_id, message, count, earliest_timestamp}. Limit output to top 20 groups ordered by count desc. 2) From log.csv filter rows in the same timestamp range for the same cmdb_ids where log_name == 'log.error_count'. Return rows sorted by timestamp ascending with columns {timestamp, cmdb_id, value} (limit to top 50 rows). If any of the requested data is missing, explicitly return an empty list for that part and a brief note."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed: global-threshold calculation for key frontend pods; anomaly detection within the incident window (1647779400–1647779999) showing earliest anomalies at 1647779400; trace snapshot at that timestamp showing very high frontend trace.row_count and heavy downstream calls to productcatalogservice; and log analysis showing大量 warning/error messages on frontend-2/0/1 starting at the onset (messages: 'severity: warning, message: failed to retrieve...') and elevated log.error_count values from 20:30 onward. Metric signals: frontend-2 (node-5) has highest CPU and FS usage; frontend2-0 (node-6) shows measurable CPU throttling but had no error logs in the window. Trace durations are small (sub-second), with the largest p95 on frontend2-0 (~0.108s). From these results we can already deduce the failure onset time is 1647779400 (2022-03-20 20:30:00 UTC+8) and that frontend pods are the primary faulty components (they show both metric anomalies and voluminous warning logs). However, whether the root cause is an upstream service failure (downstream service causing frontends to fail to retrieve), or a frontend-local issue (resource exhaustion, networking), is still ambiguous. To decide between those, we need to check whether any traces at the onset timestamp indicate errors or abnormal counts/responses at downstream services (productcatalogservice, checkoutservice), i.e., look for trace fields that indicate errors/failure counts or non-success responses. If downstream services show error traces at the same onset, they are likely root cause; otherwise the frontend itself (or its node-level constraints) is more likely the root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From trace.csv at timestamp == 1647779400, search only the components: frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, frontend2-0, checkoutservice-0, checkoutservice-1, checkoutservice-2, productcatalogservice-0, productcatalogservice-1, productcatalogservice-2. Return rows whose trace_name contains any of these substrings (case-sensitive match): 'error', 'fail', 'failed', 'response', 'status', 'exception', 'success'. Provide a compact JSON with two parts: 1) matches_top: up to 50 matched rows sorted by value descending, each row {timestamp, cmdb_id, trace_name, value}; 2) matches_counts: per-component counts of matched rows for the requested components (include components with 0 matches). If no matches found return empty matches_top and counts with zeros plus a short note stating 'no error-like traces at onset timestamp'. Keep output strictly bounded."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the workflow: computed global thresholds for key frontend pods, detected metric anomalies concentrated at timestamp 1647779400 (2022-03-20 20:30:00 UTC+8), inspected traces at that timestamp (frontends show huge row_count and many downstream calls to productcatalogservice), and examined logs (error_logs and log.error_count) which show many warning messages on frontend-2/0/1 with the short form 'severity: warning, message: failed to retrieve...' and elevated log.error_count beginning at the onset minute. Trace error-like metrics exist but their values are zero at the onset minute, so traces do not directly show downstream service failures. Metric signals show frontend-2 has highest CPU/FS usage and frontend2-0 exhibits CPU throttling but produced no error logs. What remains unclear is whether frontends failed because of an upstream/backend service failure, network/timeouts, or frontend-local resource issues. The repeated error log text likely contains the key (e.g., which upstream failed or HTTP/status/timeout details). Therefore we need the exact error log message texts (top groups) for frontends in the incident window to identify the reason.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From error_logs.csv filter rows with timestamp between 1647779400 and 1647779999 inclusive and cmdb_id in [frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2]. Group by the full message text and return up to the top 20 groups ordered by count descending. For each group return these fields only: {message (full text, trimmed to 1000 characters if longer), count, earliest_timestamp}. Keep output strictly bounded to these 20 rows and these columns; do NOT return raw ungrouped rows."
}

